  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\nS(\\omega)\n=\n2\\hbar\n\\coth\\left(\n\\frac{\\hbar\\omega}{2k_B T_{\\mathrm{eff}}}\n\\right)\n\\operatorname{Im}R(\\omega).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Effective Temperature Split.}\n\\begin{equation}\nT_{\\mathrm{eff}}\n=\nT_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{th}}\n+\nT_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{TZP}} .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $S(\\omega)$ be the noise spectrum and $R(\\omega)$ the response function.  \nDissipation is encoded by the imaginary part:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\operatorname{Im}R(\\omega).\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe fluctuation factor is set by the effective thermal and zero-point scale:\n\\begin{equation}\n2\\hbar\n\\coth\\left(\n\\frac{\\hbar\\omega}{2k_B T_{\\mathrm{eff}}}\n\\right).\n\\end{equation}\n\nMultiplying the two pieces gives:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\nS(\\omega)\n=\n2\\hbar\n\\coth\\left(\n\\frac{\\hbar\\omega}{2k_B T_{\\mathrm{eff}}}\n\\right)\n\\operatorname{Im}R(\\omega).\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nNoise and response are coupled through an effective temperature that includes ordinary thermal and TZP contributions.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
